  "name": "Depression - Comprehensive Provider Query",
  "description": "Simulates a primary care provider identifying their complete depression population. The PheKB algorithm uses four longitudinal data sources: diagnoses, antidepressant medications, depression scale measures (PHQ-9), and psychotherapy records. Real-world identification primarily uses the union of diagnosis codes and antidepressant prescriptions. The Path C heavy distribution (~40% meds without dx) makes this query especially important — a Condition-only query will dramatically underestimate the depression-treated population.",
  "prompt": "I need to identify my complete depression patient population for a quality improvement initiative on PHQ-9 screening. From clinical experience, I know depression patients are documented in different ways: some have a formal diagnosis code (MDD, recurrent depression, dysthymia), and a substantial number are on antidepressants — particularly SSRIs — without a depression diagnosis ever being formally coded. Many SSRI prescriptions are written empirically for symptoms (low mood, anxiety, insomnia) without a definitive diagnosis.\n\nPlease run multiple FHIR queries to capture the full population:\n1. Patients with any depression diagnosis (MDD, recurrent depression, dysthymia, or unspecified depressive disorder)\n2. Patients prescribed antidepressants (SSRIs, SNRIs, atypicals)\n\nFor each query, return the matching resources. I want the union of all patients found across both approaches.",
  "metadata": {
    "implementation_guide": "US Core 5.0.0",
    "multi_query": true,
    "algorithm_path": "comprehensive",
    "algorithm_path_description": "Union of depression dx codes (Paths A+B) and antidepressant Rx (Paths A+C). Path C is especially heavy in this phenotype because SSRI prescribing without formal dx is common in primary care. An LLM that only queries Condition will substantially underestimate the population.",
